g.title: exhaust is in a way the reverse of switch, if a substream is ongoing and a new one pops up, the new one is ignored

text.tspan: without flattening we’d end up with a stream where each value is a new stream
merge will immediately subscribe to all substreams, and pass values as they appear on the substream
switch is only ever subscribed to one substream
when a new one comes along, the previous one is aborted
when concat encounters a new substream while a previous one is not completed yet
it will simply ‘hold on’ to it and start subscribing as soon as the previous one completes
exhaust is in a way the reverse of switch,
if a substream is ongoing and a new one pops up, the new one is ignored
